g.text: A learning model to predict student performanceAnagha Mudigonda | Arizona State University | HSE 531 Data Analytics

• The dataset containsno missing values(NA’s) or empty cells.• After initial data exploration, attributes with no impact on final grades were discarded.• Student attributes and their values are renamed for better understanding. One of the example is shown below.

•Dataset captures student's performance (represented with grades) in two schools. School 1 = Gabriel Pereira (GP) , school 2 = Mousinhoda Silveira (MP).•Grades are available for Mathematics and Portuguese subjects. •Each subject contains first-period grade, second-period grade, and final grade, from 0 to 20.•Also, 30 student attributes are available in the dataset such as family status, study time, absences, etc.•Summary of student attributes

•Identify attributes that impact strongly on student’s grades. •Identify correlation between first-period grade, second-period grade, with final grade (Mathematics and Portuguese).•Identify correlation between school 1 (GP) and school 2 (MS) in the final grades.
It is a tidy dataset in a long-form format, without missing data.
•Further analysis, to identify these five attributes that have a strong correlation on final grades.

train_model.s1 <-lm(portuguese.finalgrade~ portuguese.firstperiodgrade+ portuguese.secondperiodgrade+ fathers.job+ internet.home+ mothers.job, data = GP.schooldata)
Goal: Use these correlations and construct a model that can predict final grade of the student.* Column number indicates attributes that are considered for further analysis.
Students with their parents working as teachers; and internet facility at home tend to have better final grades.
First and second-period grades have a strong correlation with final grades. More number of students have final grades > 12, as compared to first & second period grades.

Train a learning model, that can predict the final grades for school 1 (GP) and school 2 (MS) using these five student attributes.Figure 2Father’s statusFigure 3Mother’s statusFigure 4Internet at homeFigure 5First period correlation Figure 6First, second and final grade correlationFigure 7Second period correlation
